arch:note.arch:string: The purpose of the daily journal was to record the activities taking place in a trench each day. This included which loci were excavated, how and why loci were excavated and the ongoing impressions of the relationships among loci. It should be noted that journals record the actions, impressions and ideas of trench supervisors during the excavations. They are not, therefore, the final interpretations or syntheses of the emerging data.

arch:internalDocument.arch:string:
Daily Trench Journal

Area F, Trench 7

May 29, 2005

C. Painter

Today I was again short two workmen for most of the day as they cleaned out old trenches to be reopened this season. A 10 cm deep pick pass was completed in fill L7139 which continues to contain no visible features apart from pit 7146 in the southeast corner which is still cutting this locus and a small ashy deposit that is bordering what could be a mud brick wall. However with vigorous scraping and spraying, the outline of this possible feature is almost impossible to trace at this time.

A notable find from today in fill 7139 was a partially reconstructable pot (KT26). It was attempted to recover this pot as whole as possible, however the pot itself seems to have been burned or fired at an extremely high temperature therefore rendering the vessel highly friable. Therefore KT 26 was assigned to the vessel fragments and KT 27 from the same locus was assigned to the soil inside the pot which upon initial inspection, contained small animal bones.

Work also continued in pit L7162, which has now been found to expand into a truly circular pit. On its eastern edge, the pit cuts into wall 7153 which can be seen in the section profile. On the western edge of the pit, the eastern edge of wall 7163 can be seen though whether the pit actually cuts this wall is unclear. A small 10 cm diameter animal burrow is present in the western section profile of the pit as well.

The pit on its northern edge seems to cut into fill 7161 which is still being excavated. What is being recovered below 7161 is another burnt plaster surface that is also bonded with wall 7163 on its eastern face. In elevation, this second burnt surface can been estimated as contemporaneous to the burnt surface 7168 located on the western side of wall 7163, the latter of which is also bonded with plaster.

The Household Archaeology Protocol (HAP) was also employed with pebble surface 7166 under fill 7156. The HAP sample received KT number 1 and contained a total of seven liters of material. The remainder of the surface was not excavated as there may be more present or below fill L7157. The reason the HAP sample was collected today before the rest of the surface can be uncovered is to prevent further damage to what surface area is exposed already.

Along these lines, finally today excavation began in L7157 where the top most layer of fill was removed to uncover a pebbled surface with flat-lying pot sherds. It was found that this surface does in fact connect with surface L7159 and thus, this new western extension will be included within this initial locus. Thus far only part of the new surface has been uncovered and is sloping upwards as excavations continue west along L7157. Several progress photographs were taken and this surface will be fully excavated tomorrow with possibility for an additional HAP sample.
